WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.220
My name is Louis Kirvan.

00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:09.240
Thank you all for coming.

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:13.300
So I don't have my notes, so I'm going to do my best because I can't extend the displays

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:16.240
on this computer, but I think I'll do okay.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:21.040
So this presentation, first of all, let me start off.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:22.200
I'm Louis Kirvan.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:27.480
I'm a research manager at the Consumer Finance Protection Bureau, and I'm supposed to say

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:28.480
this.

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:29.680
I am not a representative of the U.S. government.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:31.240
I am just myself right now.

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:34.959
I don't know if you can tell, but I'm not.

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:43.439
The point of this talk is to help data analysts with words, and I think words are actually

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:44.959
super important for data analysts.

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:49.340
If you've ever communicated with a leader in your organization, you'll know that a lot

00:00:49.340 --> 00:00:55.799
of communication about data actually flows through words and that getting good at words

00:00:55.799 --> 00:00:59.799
is really going to differentiate you as a data person.

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:05.720
So the first part of this talk is about identifying situations when you're going to need more

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:06.720
words.

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:07.720
Right?

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:08.720
So that's part one.

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:12.320
Part two is how to make words a little bit easier to work with.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:16.480
So this is focusing on a couple things, but also when you want to actually generate text,

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:20.720
it's going to give you some tips, a few tips to sort of help you generate text.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:22.959
So that's the structure of this talk.

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:23.959
Let's get rolling.

00:01:23.959 --> 00:01:25.519
All right.

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:27.239
So chapter one.

00:01:27.239 --> 00:01:30.800
When do you need more words?

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:35.199
So this is probably the most familiar diagram at the conference, and everyone's seen this

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:36.199
like way too many times.

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:38.360
It's kind of funny that I put it in here.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:44.040
But this document really captures a lot about the data products process, the process of

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:48.400
creating data products, but I think it leaves out one really important thing.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:52.519
You're actually in the middle of that cycle, right?

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:53.519
And you're doing stuff.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:54.519
Like, there you are.

00:01:54.519 --> 00:01:55.519
Hands on hips.

00:01:55.519 --> 00:02:01.279
So you're in the middle of the cycle, and you're actually doing stuff and gaining context

00:02:01.279 --> 00:02:03.599
as that cycle sort of spins around you, right?

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:06.360
You're actually learning about the data, learning about the analysis, learning about what the

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:07.680
goals are.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:09.839
So you might do some stuff like this.

00:02:09.839 --> 00:02:12.800
You might look at the application that generates the data.

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:15.240
You might read a survey instrument.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.059
You might talk to application users.

00:02:18.059 --> 00:02:23.320
You might read the data documentation if you're extremely lucky.

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:29.880
You might read relevant research or talk to experts that know about how and why the data

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:30.880
was generated.

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:34.679
In my opinion, that's all statistics and data science, too.

00:02:34.679 --> 00:02:36.520
That's all important stuff.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:40.839
And knowing about the context of your data is how you don't make really stupid errors.

00:02:40.839 --> 00:02:45.919
So it's super important, and it's something that I think we don't emphasize enough, actually.

00:02:45.919 --> 00:02:47.000
All right.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:48.639
So you did your analysis.

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:50.880
You got all this context.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:52.399
And it's time to communicate.

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:53.600
This is the fun part.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:55.320
I was really good at this.

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:56.320
Right?

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:01.360
I don't want to knock on dashboards too much.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:04.800
I've built a lot of dashboards, actually, in my life.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.240
And this dashboard actually might be fine for someone.

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:13.759
It's just what I got when I Googled the busiest dashboard or something like that.

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:16.000
So I think that dashboards are fine.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.479
But when you reach for a communication tool, you want to think a little bit before you

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:27.039
grab something that's very visually dense or has a lot of moving parts.

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:32.639
So before you communicate, you want to think about your audience.

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:36.440
And so the rest of this first part is going to be a little bit about how you think about

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:39.360
your audience.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:43.720
You want to bring people along on your journey.

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:49.039
So people need to be brought along.

00:03:49.039 --> 00:03:55.639
And a great first question to ask is how much of that context I built up during my

00:03:55.639 --> 00:03:58.839
analysis does my audience share?

00:03:58.839 --> 00:04:02.500
If they don't share the context, it's going to be a difficult journey.

00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:08.399
How much do you need to pack to get that person to the destination you want them to go to?

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:13.000
So I have a couple of limit cases here, examples from my own work.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.480
So earlier this year, I wrote a report to Congress.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:22.519
It's like a required by law, and it's about credit reporting consumer complaints.

00:04:22.519 --> 00:04:26.760
It's got six charts in it, two tables, yeah, okay, cool.

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:30.839
Started in our markdown, and it's got 50 pages of context.

00:04:30.839 --> 00:04:32.720
Congress is one limit case.

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:34.839
Congress needs a lot of stuff.

00:04:34.839 --> 00:04:39.119
They need detailed explanations of all the fields and all the key terms.

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:43.200
They need to know about the data collection process, and they need to know about the law

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:46.720
that governs the data collection, and all that context.

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:52.799
I actually have a JD, so that part helped me here, but Congress needs a lot of stuff.

00:04:52.799 --> 00:04:54.920
So that's like one limit case.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:58.320
Another limit case is your immediate team, right?

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:06.839
So a ways back, I made this dashboard, took me a day, got three charts in it, six KPIs,

00:05:06.839 --> 00:05:08.200
less than a paragraph of text.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:09.200
Beautiful, right?

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:12.200
It's me and my team tracking something.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:13.760
The labels are kind of terse.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:18.600
I don't really describe the KPIs, because there are KPIs, we know what they are.

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:21.760
The data elements are just named what they are in the system, right?

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:24.079
So this is the other extreme.

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:26.359
You're likely going to be somewhere in the middle, right?

00:05:26.359 --> 00:05:28.000
But these are the two limit cases.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:33.519
So I have another example that I think, oh, so just to kind of sum up that idea, less

00:05:33.519 --> 00:05:39.519
shared context means more context words are going to be in your data product.

00:05:39.519 --> 00:05:44.160
More shared context means you can kind of include less context in your product, but

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:48.359
you should still document it, because you might forget, other people might work on it.

00:05:48.359 --> 00:05:49.359
So it's kind of a seesaw there.

00:05:49.359 --> 00:05:54.899
You can go, does it end up in the documentation, or does it end up in the data product?

00:05:54.899 --> 00:05:57.200
So here's another example.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:01.119
Moving from an internal set of tools to something external.

00:06:01.119 --> 00:06:06.160
I like this example, because it's the same data presented to two different audiences.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.519
So the internal tool is an interactive Tableau dashboard.

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:15.839
It's got like a lot of charts, dozens of charts, you know, Tableau is good for that.

00:06:15.839 --> 00:06:19.480
And then, you know, like the other example, the field names just correspond to the system

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:20.480
names.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:24.000
It's kind of a typical KPI type dashboard for your team.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.079
But when this team went to sort of report out on this stuff, you know, they started

00:06:29.079 --> 00:06:34.519
with this, and they kind of just started to repurpose it for external communication, you

00:06:34.519 --> 00:06:35.519
know.

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:40.160
And they share this with banks, and we're sort of assessing their performance.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:44.480
And I knew, when I got sort of thrown into helping them, that this document was meant

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:45.480
to travel.

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:48.079
It wasn't just going to go to the person who works on this stuff every day.

00:06:48.079 --> 00:06:50.640
They were going to give it to their supervisor, and maybe their supervisor would give it to

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:51.640
someone else.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:54.540
And it probably won't go to the board of directors, but like, it could travel.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.700
And so the context had to travel with the document.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:06:59.839
So we have this much simpler version.

00:06:59.839 --> 00:07:02.679
So there's only three simple static charts.

00:07:02.679 --> 00:07:05.279
One kind of gives you a time series of your performance.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:12.359
Each one gives you your average, and then compares you against your peers, and against

00:07:12.359 --> 00:07:14.160
some sort of overall performance.

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:16.399
So that's pretty nice.

00:07:16.399 --> 00:07:21.320
Some of the charts from the internal dashboard are actually sentences and paragraphs now.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:26.160
So the names are all also defined in an introduction.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:30.799
You know, a sentence is actually, if you just like tell someone what the chart means, that's

00:07:30.799 --> 00:07:32.660
actually denser than a chart, right?

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:36.820
So in some places, we want to do that stuff.

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:41.980
I also, you know, included different text depending on thresholds and other stuff, right?

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:48.179
So some of these sentences and paragraphs didn't really apply to some of these companies.

00:07:48.179 --> 00:07:51.119
And so we thresholded it, and they just don't appear in the document.

00:07:51.119 --> 00:07:53.179
So it doesn't like bloat, and bloat, and bloat, right?

00:07:53.179 --> 00:07:58.660
So that's an example of moving from internal to external.

00:07:58.660 --> 00:08:00.500
Summarize this with some key factors.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.019
The biggest one is external, right?

00:08:03.019 --> 00:08:06.359
If they're outside your org, they don't have any of your context likely.

00:08:06.359 --> 00:08:10.339
But even within your org, you can think about levels of externality, right?

00:08:10.339 --> 00:08:14.339
You know, there's your immediate team, and then there's concentric circles.

00:08:14.339 --> 00:08:17.779
And as you kind of move further away from your team, you need to be adding more context

00:08:17.779 --> 00:08:19.200
in.

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:24.619
Another key factor is if you're kind of dealing with a less technical audience.

00:08:24.619 --> 00:08:28.940
Less technical audiences mean you can't use shortcuts that you might use when you're communicating

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:29.940
with a technical audience.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:34.179
You're not just going to present an ROC curve to your executive and say, hey, look, my model's

00:08:34.179 --> 00:08:35.179
really good.

00:08:35.179 --> 00:08:36.179
Look.

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:37.619
Because they're not going to get that, right?

00:08:37.619 --> 00:08:42.020
So you have to think about adding more context in for those folks.

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:45.739
Decision makers are important because they actually need context to trust what you're

00:08:45.739 --> 00:08:47.059
telling them.

00:08:47.059 --> 00:08:50.979
If they don't have appropriate context, they're not going to trust you, and they're going

00:08:50.979 --> 00:08:53.659
to reject your findings, even if you're right, right?

00:08:53.659 --> 00:08:56.780
You can pound the table all you want, but they need enough context to trust you.

00:08:56.780 --> 00:08:58.859
And I've had this happen to me.

00:08:58.859 --> 00:09:02.859
It's pretty disappointing, honestly, when you're like, look, it works.

00:09:02.859 --> 00:09:03.859
It's great.

00:09:03.859 --> 00:09:05.500
And they're like, I don't know what this is even, right?

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:08.020
So you have to give them that appropriate context.

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:12.020
Time crunched is actually counterintuitive in a way, right?

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:16.859
Time crunched people, like, you want to give them as little as possible in some ways, but

00:09:16.859 --> 00:09:18.900
you're only going to get them one time, right?

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:23.380
So those time crunched people have one shot, and if they don't walk away with the context

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:27.380
that's necessary to understand this, they'll either misinterpret it, not interpret it,

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:28.859
or forget about it, right?

00:09:28.859 --> 00:09:30.460
So those time crunched people are important, too.

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:35.739
So those are some key factors when thinking about this question of, like, what should

00:09:35.739 --> 00:09:36.739
I build?

00:09:36.739 --> 00:09:40.619
How much context do I need to put in it for my audience?

00:09:40.619 --> 00:09:42.500
All right.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:45.739
Chapter two, how to make words a little bit easier.

00:09:45.739 --> 00:09:46.739
All right.

00:09:46.739 --> 00:09:47.739
I'm done, guys.

00:09:47.739 --> 00:09:48.739
That's it.

00:09:48.739 --> 00:09:49.739
Actually, now I'm done.

00:09:49.739 --> 00:09:50.739
Not really.

00:09:50.739 --> 00:09:57.020
I actually have some tips.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:04.179
So my tips are just three kind of simple things, use some templates, use design resources,

00:10:04.179 --> 00:10:06.179
and then partner up.

00:10:06.179 --> 00:10:08.059
All right.

00:10:08.059 --> 00:10:10.059
Let's start with the first one.

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:12.659
So the context here is you're generating text.

00:10:12.659 --> 00:10:17.539
I don't know if you've ever generated a document with a lot of text.

00:10:17.539 --> 00:10:21.179
What happens is your environment just gets littered with variables.

00:10:21.179 --> 00:10:23.780
There's all kinds of different variables.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:27.020
Some of these documents I put together are 10, 15 pages.

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:28.900
You've computed 10 different means.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:30.380
They all have different names.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:34.580
And when you make a mistake, debugging is annoying and hard.

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:40.619
And so what you can do is actually add a language engine that will allow you to put templates

00:10:40.619 --> 00:10:43.020
in your R Markdown document and then fill them with data.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:49.619
This is a really simple language, like, really simple function you can just add at the top

00:10:49.619 --> 00:10:51.659
of your Markdown file.

00:10:51.659 --> 00:10:53.619
It's a knitter engine here.

00:10:53.619 --> 00:10:54.859
And this works in Corto.

00:10:54.859 --> 00:10:55.859
I just did it.

00:10:55.859 --> 00:10:56.859
Right?

00:10:56.859 --> 00:10:57.859
It works.

00:10:57.859 --> 00:10:58.859
So you add this.

00:10:58.859 --> 00:11:01.340
This is using whisker, which uses mustache templates.

00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:04.539
I'll talk about that in just one second.

00:11:04.539 --> 00:11:08.059
Options code, that's just the stuff that's in your code block.

00:11:08.059 --> 00:11:10.400
So you put your template in there.

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:13.559
And then as an argument, you supply some data.

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:18.400
And then it will render and make something nice for you.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:19.400
You can do it with glue, too.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:20.400
Right?

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:21.400
So here it is with glue.

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:22.400
Basically the same function.

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:23.400
You need more stuff for glue.

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:26.520
This would be quite a bit longer if I were to really put this together for glue.

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:29.799
But just so you can see, the basics are the same.

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:32.880
This still works, but there's stuff you want to do.

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:34.280
All right.

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:40.880
So here's an example of just that concept of taking your namespace or using a list as

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:45.479
a namespace so that you don't basically end up cluttering your namespace.

00:11:45.479 --> 00:11:47.559
So I'm generating one sentence here.

00:11:47.559 --> 00:11:50.960
And there's one, two, three, four, five or so, six variables.

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.799
There's a bunch of variables just for one sentence.

00:11:53.799 --> 00:11:54.799
Right?

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:58.640
And what I like to do is when I have a document with some structure in it, like a section,

00:11:58.640 --> 00:11:59.719
I'll have a list.

00:11:59.719 --> 00:12:04.080
And I'll pack all the variables for that section into the list that's named the same.

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:09.320
And then my environment stays relatively pretty, debugging gets easier, and my mental load

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:14.039
as a developer doesn't sort of go haywire completely.

00:12:14.039 --> 00:12:17.640
And so then when you go to do this, it's actually pretty simple.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:22.299
You have right here, this is a mustache template, a really simple one.

00:12:22.299 --> 00:12:23.299
Mustache is great.

00:12:23.299 --> 00:12:24.299
It has some other...

00:12:24.299 --> 00:12:25.299
It's a logic list template.

00:12:25.299 --> 00:12:26.299
So it's very...

00:12:26.299 --> 00:12:27.500
It's almost like Markdown in a way.

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:32.960
But you can add some basically data-dependent stuff that will make stuff appear or not appear.

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:35.840
There's a few other nice little features.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:37.239
But it kind of just works.

00:12:37.239 --> 00:12:38.880
So there's the data, filling it in.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:41.080
The sentence now exists.

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:42.200
And there's a glue version.

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:45.200
You need some post-processing on glue to make it not have quotes and stuff.

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:49.559
The real function I use is longer, but I didn't want to go into all that detail.

00:12:49.559 --> 00:12:50.559
So that's tip one.

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:53.200
I think it's pretty helpful.

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.919
And if you do more of this stuff, especially when you're generating a lot of text, it's

00:12:56.919 --> 00:12:58.599
super helpful.

00:12:58.599 --> 00:12:59.760
Tip two.

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:02.280
Use existing design resources.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:08.039
Design is like super-duper important when you're making a document that you want people

00:13:08.039 --> 00:13:09.039
to read.

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:14.520
You need consistency and you need signposting to make the document useful.

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:19.400
And I kind of took a weird path to being a researcher and data analyst.

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:22.799
I've got a degree in African history and a JD.

00:13:22.799 --> 00:13:27.000
So I spent like 30-ish years trying to make other kinds of good documents.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.039
So some of this stuff is natural to me.

00:13:30.039 --> 00:13:33.859
But I think it should be more natural to data analysts as well.

00:13:33.859 --> 00:13:38.840
So someone at your org has probably thought about those issues, that signposting, that

00:13:38.840 --> 00:13:39.840
consistency.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.200
And they have resources for you.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:44.000
So you should steal them, basically.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.640
So it's almost as easy as this, right?

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:53.000
So you have in your YAML a reference doc.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.359
The actual package comes with a reference doc.

00:13:55.359 --> 00:14:00.719
You look at that reference doc, it shows you all the styles that you need.

